{
  "metadata": {
    "intent": "Generalist-dominance probe (issue #325): does the conjunction of structural fragility (cost-structure trade-off #9) and functional incompatibility (trade-off #2, substrate-anchored autotrophy/uptake vs. mobility) confine broad generalists to a niche WITHOUT a committed cross-trait interaction maintenance term? Four archetypes compete in one viable world: specialist producers, specialist mobile consumers, BROAD generalists (autotrophy + heterotrophy + mobility -- the rooted-producer + roving-hunter the design rules out), and COMPATIBLE generalists (autotrophy + heterotrophy, sessile -- the real-mixotroph case the design predicts is possible-but-non-dominant). The broad and compatible generalists are identical except for mobility (0.5 vs 0.0), so their divergent fates isolate the sessile/mobile incompatibility axis as an in-run control. No interaction term, no mobility maintenance (mobility_maintenance_cost = 0), and no wear (wear_rate = 0) are in play -- the only forces penalising breadth are the committed structural fragility (entropy death threshold) and emergent incompatibility (plus the breadth-neutral movement cost). The breadth/dominance measure is read off survivor traits by crates/explorers-genesis-eval/src/bin/probe_generalist.rs and corroborated by the evaluator's own generalist_dominance gate in observed.json.",
    "source_issue": 325,
    "roster": "24 specialist producers (autotrophy 0.45, sessile) on a ring (r=32) as the sustaining base; 8 specialist consumers (heterotrophy 0.5, mobility 0.3); 10 broad generalists (autotrophy 0.5 + heterotrophy 0.5 + mobility 0.5, reserve 80 -- energy-advantaged); 10 compatible generalists (autotrophy 0.5 + heterotrophy 0.5, sessile, reserve 80). All non-producers seeded just inside the ring within feeding reach (eff_heterotrophy * contact_range_coefficient = 0.5 * 5.0 = 2.5 units) of prey -- the steel-man placement giving generalists light AND prey.",
    "probes": "generalist_dominance",
    "prediction": "live",
    "rationale": "The design predicts generalists are possible-but-non-dominant: compatible (both-sessile) mixotrophs persist as a confined niche, while the broadest generalist (rooted producer + roving hunter) is ruled out by functional incompatibility -- mobility breaks the substrate-anchored stillness autotrophy and nutrient uptake require (a moving body leaves its local nutrient cell and cannot sustain feeding contact) -- compounded by structural fragility: the broad generalist's higher trait-vector entropy raises its death threshold as a fraction of peak structure, so it dies after a smaller structural loss. Per-trait maintenance convexity is breadth-neutral and does NOT contribute (world-rules #5). So the world should stay live and differentiated (multi-cluster), broad generalists should fail to establish, and any surviving generalists (the sessile mixotrophs) should hold a minority of energy -- NOT trip the generalist_dominance gate. A finding that broad generalists dominate would instead warrant the reserve cross-trait interaction maintenance term (filed as a separate follow-up, not implemented here).",
    "geometry": "Producers ring at r=32; consumers, broad and compatible generalists interleaved at r=28-30, all within the 2.5-unit feeding reach of ring producers so the heterotrophic archetypes genuinely have prey access (the spatial realisation that makes the dominance test fair rather than prey-starved).",
    "status": "current -- every WorldParameter specified explicitly (example4/example10 template); inherits example9's proven-viable producer-ring economy with contact_range_coefficient widened to 5.0 so non-producers can reach prey."
  },
